1 Between two foods, distant and tempting
2 in the same way, one would die of hunger
3 before a free man would bring one to his teeth;

4 thus one would stand for a year between two cravings
5 of fierce wolves, fearing them equally;
6 thus one would stand, a dog between two does:

13 Beatrice did as Daniel did,
14 rousing Nebuchadnezzar from his anger,
15 which had unjustly made him fierce;

31 have their seats in no other heaven
32 than these spirits who have just appeared to you,
33 nor do they have more or fewer years in their existence;

43 For this reason, Scripture condescends
44 to your faculty, and attributes
45 feet and hands to God and means something else;

52 He says that the soul returns to its star,
53 believing that it was separated from it
54 when nature gave it form;

85 it would have pushed them back along the path
86 from which they were drawn, as soon as they were released;
87 but such a firm will is too rare.

94 I have certainly put it in your mind
95 that a blessed soul could not lie,
96 because it is always close to the first truth;

97 and then you could hear from Piccarda
98 that the affection for the veil held Constance;
99 so that she seems to contradict me here.

100 Many times already, brother, it has happened
101 that, to escape danger, against one's will
102 one did what was not right to do;

109 Absolute will does not consent to harm;
110 but it consents to it insofar as it fears,
111 if it withdraws, falling into greater suffering.

115 Such was the rippling of the holy stream
116 that issued from the source from which all truth flows;
117 thus it put one desire and the other at peace.

121 my affection is not so deep
122 that it is enough to return to you grace for grace;
123 but may He who sees and can do so answer for this.
